# Architecture — {{.app_name}}

This document describes the topology and operational model for HSS Databricks
apps generated from `hss-lakebase-app-template`. It is the source of truth
that the wizard prompts, `databricks.yml`, `app.yaml`, the scripts, and the
GitHub Actions workflows all align to.

## 1. Topology — one project per use-case group

```
Databricks Account
│
├── workspace: dev   (https://...-dev.cloud.databricks.com)
│   └── Lakebase Autoscaling projects   ← one PROJECT per use-case group
│       ├── clinical-informatics
│       │   └── branch: production    (no_expiry=True)
│       │       ├── database: claims_triage_db
│       │       ├── database: care_gaps_db
│       │       ├── database: ...                  (5–10 apps total)
│       │       └── database: shared_reference_db  (optional, group-wide)
│       ├── rev-cycle-analytics
│       │   └── branch: production
│       │       └── ... 5–10 databases ...
│       └── dicom-imaging
│           └── ... same pattern ...
│
├── workspace: test  (same 3 projects, mirrored)
└── workspace: prod  (same 3 projects, mirrored)
```

Why this shape:

- **Project = use-case group.** Apps that share data and ownership share a
  project. Apps that are independent get separate projects. Project
  boundaries are also the unit of Lakebase ACL — `hss-clinical-informatics-*`
  groups get access to the `clinical-informatics` project but not to
  `rev-cycle-analytics`.
- **Database per app, all on `production` branch.** Each app owns its own
  schema and indexes (per Juliana: "I can't have a shared table because the
  indexes are going to be different on each application"), but shares the
  serverless compute pool of its sibling apps. This is cheaper than
  one-project-per-app because per-app projects each carry their own minimum
  compute floor.
- **`production` branch is canonical.** It is created `no_expiry=True` and
  is never deleted. Schema migrations land here. The app SP connects to
  this branch in steady state.
- **PR branches fork off `production`** with a 7-day TTL and 30-minute idle
  timeout. They are for validating schema migrations *only*. They are not
  used for promotion or rollback.
- **Workspaces are the env boundary.** dev/test/prod each carry the same
  set of project IDs (`clinical-informatics`, etc.) — no `-dev` / `-prod`
  suffixes. Promotion = redeploy the app code to the next workspace; the
  project name stays the same. Cross-workspace data flows (e.g. UC sync)
  happen via separate sync pipelines, never by pointing a dev app at a
  prod project.

This app, `{{.app_name}}`, belongs to use-case group **`{{.use_case_group}}`**
and writes to database **`{{.database_name}}`**.

## 2. Three layers of access control

| Layer | Identities | Provisioned by | Enforces |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Lakebase project ACL** | App SP, AD groups | `apply_group_grants.py` (groups) + manual for app SP | who can reach the project at all |
| **Postgres role grants** | App SP, AD groups, individual users (via Data API) | `apply_grants.py`, `apply_group_grants.py`, `databricks_create_role()` | per-schema / per-table CRUD privileges |
| **Row-level security** | per-user / per-tenant | RLS policies in your migrations (`CREATE POLICY ...`) | per-row visibility based on `current_user` |

All three layers stack — a group needs **(a)** project ACL CAN_USE, **(b)**
a Postgres role plus GRANTs, and **(c)** RLS policies that match its
identity (if RLS is enabled on the table). This is intentional defense in
depth: a misconfiguration at any one layer fails closed.

## 3. Identity model

```
Browser ── HTTPS ──┬── App (FastAPI) ──┬── Lakebase (Postgres)
                   │                   │   ├── as App SP for app's own writes
                   │                   │   └── as user (impersonated) for OBO reads
                   │                   │
                   │                   └── Unity Catalog
                   │                       ├── as App SP for background reads
                   │                       └── as user (OBO) for governed reads
                   │
                   └── (optional) Data API ── Lakebase as authenticated user
```

- **App SP** (auto-provisioned at first `apps create`). Used for:
  - App's own writes to its Lakebase database (`server/db/lakebase.py`)
  - Background reads from Unity Catalog
  - Migration runs in CI (impersonated by the CI principal)
- **On-Behalf-Of (OBO) user token** (`x-forwarded-access-token` header).
  Used for UC reads where the end user's UC row filters / column masks
  must apply. {{if eq .use_obo "yes"}}**Enabled for this app.**{{else}}*Not enabled for this app — set `use_obo=yes` at scaffold time to enable.*{{end}}
- **Data API authenticator role.** When `expose_data_api=yes`, the Lakebase
  setup creates an `authenticator` Postgres role that assumes the
  identity of the OAuth bearer in each HTTP request. Per-user RLS policies
  apply via `current_user`. {{if eq .expose_data_api "yes"}}**Enabled for this app.**{{else}}*Not enabled for this app.*{{end}}

## 4. Decision tree — when to create what

```
Need a new app for HSS?
│
├── Does it logically belong to an existing use-case group?
│   │
│   ├── YES → reuse the existing project. Just give the app its own
│   │        database name and run the per-app deploy. No bootstrap needed.
│   │
│   └── NO  → before scaffolding the app:
│             1. Have platform admin run, in each env workspace:
│                  python scripts/bootstrap_use_case_group.py \
│                    --project <new-group> --database <app1_db>
│             2. Provision the AD groups
│                (hss-<new-group>-admins/writers/readers)
│             3. Then scaffold the first app with use_case_group=<new-group>
│
├── Does it need shared reference data (synced UC tables) used by other
│   apps in the same group?
│   │
│   ├── YES → set needs_shared_reference_data=yes at scaffold time.
│   │        The shared_reference_db is created once by bootstrap; subsequent
│   │        apps in the group get read-only access via permissions.yaml.
│   │
│   └── NO  → app has its own per-app DB only.
│
└── Does it need a REST API on top of Postgres for non-FastAPI consumers
    (BI tools, Postman, low-code platforms)?
    │
    ├── YES → set expose_data_api=yes. Adds the Data API enablement step
    │         to the deploy workflow.
    │
    └── NO  → app exposes FastAPI routes only. Default.
```

## 5. Cost model

Use-case-group projects are Autoscaling, so the cost shape is:

- **Idle compute = $0.** Scale-to-zero kicks in after `idle_timeout_min`
  (default 30 min). Apps with no traffic pay nothing for compute.
- **Active compute = pay per second** at the project's `min_compute` —
  `max_compute` slider. Set these per-group based on the apps' peak
  concurrent QPS.
- **Storage = pay for diff.** PR branches use copy-on-write storage, so a
  PR branch's marginal storage cost is only the size of writes it
  performed during validation. They also auto-delete on PR close (and
  fall back to 7-day TTL safety in case the workflow misses the close).
- **Compute scales independently per branch.** A burst of PR validation
  jobs does not slow down the production branch.

## 6. Where to look for what

- **`databricks.yml`** — variables, target wiring, environment binding.
- **`app.yaml`** — runtime env vars baked at `bundle deploy` time.
- **`server/db/lakebase.py`** — SDK-runtime connect pattern, credential refresh.
- **`permissions.yaml`** — declarative grants (app SP + groups + UC).
- **`scripts/bootstrap_use_case_group.py`** — one-time per (env x group) setup.
- **`scripts/apply_grants.py`** — per-app SP grants (runs every deploy).
- **`scripts/apply_group_grants.py`** — AD group grants (runs every deploy).
- **`scripts/enable_data_api.py`** — Data API setup for opt-in apps.
- **`scripts/lakebase_branch.py`** — PR branch lifecycle.
- **`scripts/rollback_migration.py`** — alembic downgrade + PITR rollback.
- **`docs/RUNBOOK.md`** — operational procedures.
- **`docs/PROD_LOCKDOWN.md`** — workspace-side enforcement (deploy hardening).
- **`docs/DATA_CLASSIFICATION.md`** — PHI/PII handling policy.
